00:02:34,400 --> 00:02:38,600
You rate eight outwards at the center, ring zero is where you have the most trust.

38
00:02:38,600 --> 00:02:45,320
And you rate eight outwards to layer three, ring three where you have the least trust.

39
00:02:45,320 --> 00:02:49,880
Next, let's talk about the concept of secure memory management.

40
00:02:49,880 --> 00:02:54,560
And this is the idea that in a system, we'll have multiple programs running.

41
00:02:54,560 --> 00:02:59,640
And each of those programs will have some data loaded into volatile memory, RAM, random

42
00:02:59,640 --> 00:03:01,600
access memory.

43
00:03:01,600 --> 00:03:05,960
And the idea behind secure memory management is that we want to make sure that if, if

44
00:03:05,960 --> 00:03:11,280
process A is accessing data in RAM, what data should be allowed to access?

45
00:03:11,280 --> 00:03:12,280
Only its own data.

46
00:03:12,280 --> 00:03:14,160
That's the idea of secure memory management.

47
00:03:14,160 --> 00:03:17,760
You allocate parts of memory to different processes.

48
00:03:17,760 --> 00:03:22,000
And then you have a component in place system that's controlling and making sure that only

49
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:26,240
process A can access process A's data in memory.

50
00:03:26,240 --> 00:03:31,240
What do you think we would fundamentally call that system that's mediating that access?

51
00:03:31,240 --> 00:03:33,040
That would be a security kernel.

52
00:03:33,040 --> 00:03:37,840
So secure memory management is about essentially implementing a security kernel that controls

53
00:03:37,840 --> 00:03:40,800
which processes can access, which data in RAM.

54
00:03:40,800 --> 00:03:45,760
And as you can see here in the diagram, process A can only access process A's data and not

55
00:03:45,760 --> 00:03:50,600
data from the operating system or other processes.

56
00:03:50,600 --> 00:03:53,040
Next we have the concept of data hiding.

57
00:03:53,040 --> 00:03:59,360
And this is the idea that we can have data at different levels of confidentiality or value.

58
00:03:59,360 --> 00:04:04,280
And the idea behind data hiding is that if you are at a lower level of confidentiality,

59
00:04:04,280 --> 00:04:06,840
then you cannot see data at higher levels.

60
00:04:06,840 --> 00:04:09,280
That data is hidden from you.

61
00:04:09,280 --> 00:04:14,680
And so data hiding is basically just an implementation of which model that John talked about.

62
00:04:14,680 --> 00:04:19,680
Which model had to do with confidential data at different layers?

63
00:04:20,680 --> 00:04:24,200
And so Bella Padula is essentially what data hiding is all about.

64
00:04:24,200 --> 00:04:30,520
If you're down at a lower level of secrecy, you can't see data at higher levels of secrecy.

